XPONENTIAL FITNESS, INC. (NYSE: XPOF)
Point of View
Fiscal Q1 2026, quarter ended March 31, 2026
(Form 10-Q, reported May 7, 2026)
================================================================

> Top-Line Performance: Revenue declined to $60.7m in Q1 FY26 from $76.9m in Q1 FY25, a (21%) / ($16.2m) YoY decrease, driven by strategic brand divestitures, fewer equipment installations, and a shift to an outsourced merchandise model — franchise revenue fell (6%), equipment revenue (61%), and merchandise revenue (90%). Systemwide same-store sales declined (6%), though North American system-wide sales rose 2% to $436.9m on a pro forma basis and total members grew 2% to ~803,000 across 3,100+ studios, indicating the consumer-facing network remains broadly stable even as the franchisor's reported revenue contracts. Full-year FY25 revenue was $314.9m vs $320.3m in FY24, a (2%) / ($5.5m) decline; management reaffirmed its full-year 2026 outlook, signalling expected H2 recovery.

> Profitability: As an asset-light franchisor, Xponential does not report a traditional gross margin; the revenue mix shift away from low-margin equipment and merchandise toward high-margin franchise royalties is structurally margin-accretive, with product costs falling sharply under the outsourced merchandise model. Operating margin expanded to 21.4% in Q1 FY26 from 12.6% in Q1 FY25, with income from operations rising to $13.0m from $9.7m, driven by a (34%) reduction in SG&A and the favourable revenue mix; this is the key profitability bright spot. Net loss narrowed to ($0.8m) in Q1 FY26 from ($2.7m) in Q1 FY25, but the improvement at the operating line was substantially offset below the line by interest expense rising to $14.5m — the high cost of the company's leveraged balance sheet is consuming nearly all of the operating profit. Adjusted EBITDA was $20.4m in Q1 FY26 (33.6% margin), down (25%) from $27.2m in Q1 FY25. Full-year FY25 context: net loss was ($53.7m), or ($1.47) per basic share, vs ($98.7m) or ($2.27) per basic share in FY24 — a narrowing, but the second consecutive year of material net losses.

> Cash Flows: Net cash used in operating activities was ($21.7m) in Q1 FY26, a sharp deterioration from $5.8m provided in Q1 FY25 — a ~$27.5m negative swing. The outflow primarily reflects the front-loading of legal settlement payments (FTC and franchisee settlements), incremental marketing spend, and adverse working-capital movements. The operating cash outflow drove a decline in cash, cash equivalents and restricted cash to $21.5m at March 31, 2026 from $45.9m at fiscal year-end — a ($24.4m) / (53%) reduction in a single quarter, an unsustainable burn rate against the remaining cash base.

> Liquidity and debt position: Cash, cash equivalents and restricted cash totalled $21.5m at March 31, 2026, down from $45.9m at fiscal year-end December 31, 2025 — a (53%) sequential decline. Against this thin cash position sits gross long-term debt of approximately $524.0m, with the new credit agreement priced at a punitive ~10.5% margin over reference rates, signalling distressed-tier pricing and a capital structure that is consuming operating cash through interest service ($14.5m in Q1 FY26 alone, annualising to ~$58m). Total liabilities exceed total assets, producing a stockholders' deficit of ($372.0m). Deferred revenue of $88.9m (largely franchise development fees recognised over multiple years) provides reported-revenue visibility but is non-cash. Xponential controls 85.1% of its main operating LLC, with 14.9% held by noncontrolling interests — an Up-C structure that complicates the capital stack.

> Working Capital: Working capital is under acute pressure from the settlement payment schedule. The combined $39.75m of legal settlements — $17.0m to the FTC over 12 months and $22.75m to 509 franchisees over 35 months — represent a defined, near-term cash drain against a $21.5m cash base, effectively requiring the settlement obligations to be funded from operating cash flow or incremental borrowing. The 30% of contractually obligated studio licenses that are more than 12 months behind development schedule (classified as inactive) represent deferred or at-risk franchise/development fee collections, further pressuring the working-capital conversion cycle.

> Operational Restructuring Plan: Xponential has executed a major portfolio rationalisation, reducing its brand count from 10 to 5 core brands (Club Pilates, StretchLab, YogaSix, Pure Barre, BFT) via divestitures of CycleBar, Rumble, Row House, AKT, Stride, and Kinrgy. The company shifted to an outsourced merchandise model (margin-accretive but revenue-dilutive) and closed 140 studios globally in FY25 against 341 gross new openings, with closures accelerating to 47 units in Q4 FY25. Approximately 30% of contractually obligated studio licenses are more than 12 months behind their development schedules and have been classified as inactive — a material signal of franchisee-level distress beneath the system-wide sales stability.

> Going Concern / Regulatory & Litigation Overhang: This is the defining feature of the credit. No explicit "substantial doubt" statement has been issued, but the convergence of risks is restructuring-defining: (i) FTC settlement of $17.0m — described as the largest consumer-redress amount ever obtained in a franchise enforcement case — to resolve Franchise Rule violations (failure to disclose former CEO Anthony Geisler's fraud litigation history and franchisee closure data); (ii) a separate $22.75m settlement with 509 current and former franchisees alleging misstatements and omissions; (iii) an ongoing criminal investigation by the U.S. Attorney's Office for the Central District of California (disclosed May 7, 2024, still open); (iv) the SEC investigation opened December 2023, which was closed in July 2025 without action; and (v) securities class actions (e.g., City of Taylor v. XPOF) alleging shareholder fraud, all tracing to the June 2023 Fuzzy Panda Research short report alleging that 8 of 10 brands were unprofitable and that more than 50% of studios never achieved a positive financial return. Combined with ($372.0m) stockholders' deficit, ~$524m of debt at distressed pricing, and negative operating cash flow, the next 12 months carry material refinancing and contingent-liability execution risk.

> Management Change: Sustained, deep C-suite and board instability. Founder and CEO Anthony Geisler was forced out in May 2024 amid the U.S. Attorney's Office probe; board member Brenda Morris served as interim CEO; former Taco Bell chief Mark King was appointed CEO but resigned in summer 2025 citing health reasons; Mike Nuzzo was appointed CEO in August 2025. The finance and operating functions remain in transition: Robert Julian was added as interim Chief Financial Officer, Erik Quade as Chief Information Officer, and Steph So as Chief Marketing Officer (effective mid-May 2026) — all within Q1 FY26. The reliance on an "interim" CFO during a period of active settlement execution, distressed-priced debt, and a live criminal investigation concentrates execution risk at the most critical seat.

> Delayed SEC filing: Not flagged based on available information — Q4/FY25 results were released February 26, 2026 and Q1 FY26 results on May 7, 2026, both on schedule, with no Form 12b-25 extension reported. Reporting controls appear intact despite prior accounting restatements (which followed the Fuzzy Panda allegations) and the ongoing federal investigation.

